Vedanta Resources Plc â€™s Konkola
Copper Mines Plc plans to raise $1.1 billion in a London initial
public offering to expand its mines in Zambia and pay debt.  Vedanta, which owns 79 percent of the company, will retain
a majority shareholding, Konkola said in a statement today.
Goldman Sachs International and JPMorgan Cazenove are joint
sponsors, global coordinators and bookrunners, the company said.  Konkola, which operates the Konkola and Nchanga mines in
Zambia, produced about 173,000 metric tons of copper in the 12
months through March 31 and had earnings before interest, taxes,
depreciation and amortization of $167.9 million in the period.
Konkola plans to produce more than 400,000 tons a year by 2014.  Konkola also plans a separate listing on the Lusaka Stock
Exchange in Zambia, it said.  Vedanta fell 86 pence, or 3.8 percent, to 2,194 pence by
the 4:30 p.m. close of trading in London.  To contact the reporter on this story:
